    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Transitional disks are thought to be sites of ongoing planet formation. One of the most extensively studied of such discs is LkCa 15, for which a variety of observations show indications of a gap with a radius of ∼50–58 AU, as well as signatures suggesting the presence of a second, inner dust disc at sub-AU separations. Additional observations have detected an object inside the gap consistent with a protoplanet of 6–15MJup. Recent imaging observations have suggested that the gap in the disc may be offset with respect to the position of the host star. If confirmed, this offset would imply a significant eccentricity in the disc which would constitute strong evidence for dynamical sculpting by one or more planets.Here we propose a simple yet powerful observational test consisting of measuring the velocity map and emission from the disc with ALMA Cycle 2 in Band 9. The unprecedented resolution of such observations will allow us to accurately measure and compare the location of both the center of mass of the system and the center of the emission, which could unambiguously confirm or reject the eccentricity associated with the presence of a planet.</prp:abstract>
